author: @JT-zt7uq
text: I just watched the movie and I think Snow White was FANTASTIC! The music was incredible, the scenes were beautiful, but what I really enjoyed the most was the simple, pure, good-vs-evil plot where good wins and evil loses. Snow White is a story of how Christ-like leadership--principles of selflessness, virtue, generosity, kindness, compassion, and grace--leads people to prosperity and true happiness. It contrasts this against the darkness of greed and jealously and clearly yet wonderfully teaches that these evil tendencies lead to sadness and spiritual poverty in individuals and nations. In the end, good wins, and evil is consumed by it's own pride. The leader who cares about others and knows their names is chosen by the people. The leader who seeks only for her own interests is destroyed by her greed. This is the type of story I can raise my children on. This is the type of story that makes society better.

text: Ok so I‚Äôve watched it excepting something bad as are all of Disney‚Äôs live actions and I was surprised as how worse it even managed to be than publicized. How on earth was this produced? Rachel Zegler is an incredibly talented singer but she has no charisma here and most certainly not the looks of the fairest of anything poor thing. What a miscast. The woke philosophy behind her casting could have been tolerable had she been right for the part but she just doesn‚Äôt have the looks. I understand that she was named Snow White because of being born on a snowy day and not because of her complexion event though that‚Äôs total betrayal to the original tale but there‚Äôs no way to make her possibly pass as ‚Äúthe fairest of them all‚Äù and certainly not fairer than Gal Gadot who once more shows how stiff and limited her acting skills are. The whole thing has zero soul and even less charisma. Zegler was great in West Side Story but again she doesn‚Äôt have the charisma or the looks of a movie star. What an embarrassing waste of budget. The animals and most importantly the dwarfs have no presence and the fact that they used an actual human dwarf to play one of Johnathan‚Äôs companions is even more mind boggling. The songs are endlessly generic and nothing stands out. It‚Äôs so bad. A pity considering how much this must have cost.

author: @FancinemaFancinema
text: Congratulations. Really. Bravo to everyone who boycotted Snow White hoping it would fail. You succeeded : the film didn‚Äôt do well at the box office. Mission accomplished. But here‚Äôs the flip side : Thanks to this failure, many projects that people were genuinely excited about have now been canceled. Aladdin 2 ‚Äî scrapped. Hercules ‚Äî suspended during the script phase. Rapunzel ‚Äî the long-awaited project ? Cancelled. So yes, you got what you wanted. But at what cost ? The irony is that Snow White still found significant success in home media sales. The film is now ranked among the top-selling physical releases worldwide. And those who bought it ? They keep it for life. Unlike a cinema ticket, a DVD doesn‚Äôt fade away. So in the end, you made a lot of noise‚Ä¶ but for what ? The result : cancelled films, an actress targeted, entire teams demoralized‚Ä¶ And a movie that still managed to reach an audience‚Äîsimply because some people chose to give it a chance. author: @mhdsy483
text: Avoid! What a monumental disappointment this new adaptation of "Snow White" is! Supposedly modern, the film is in reality nothing more than a confused collection of poorly digested ideas. The script, wanting at all costs to correct the tales of the past, falls into the trap of hyper-correction and empties the story of all its poetry and magic. The casting choices, especially for the Queen, cruelly lack the presence and credibility necessary to embody the "fairest of them all." The new songs are completely forgettable and break the rhythm of the story instead of enriching it. The visual effects, at times, are painful to watch and sadly recall a low-cost television series. It is a soulless, charmless version that betrays the spirit of the original tale without offering anything worthwhile in exchange. An hour and a half completely wasted.

author: @Amber_xo_133
text: Angelina Jolie admitted that she still has the pair of horns at home. Angelina Jolie herself picked Lana Del Rey to sing Sleeping Beauty (1959)'s "Once Upon a Dream" for the end credits. Maleficent's magic changes colour. When she is good, her magic is gold and when she is evil, her magic is green. Diaval's make-up (in human form) consisted of "crow's feet" on his face and body All the actors and actresses in Maleficent were partly chosen to be in the movie based on their uncanny resemblances and/or likeness to their respective character counterparts in Disney's Sleeping Beauty (1959). For Maleficent's horns, Angelina Jolie wore several headpieces with different weights. One headpiece was so heavy that Angelina would have neck pains right after and therefore was not appropriate for her more physically intensive scenes, such as her flight and battle scenes. Maleficent is a fairy but notably resembles more of a harpy, the hybrid, winged creature from the Greek and Roman mythologies with the parts of a woman and a bird. The last major film of special makeup effects artist Rick Baker. After this film, he retired from the industry in 2015 due to lack of good work. Maleficent's prosthetics and make-up were inspired by singer Lady Gaga, particularly on her "Born This Way" album cover. Angelina Jolie's Disney debut. The film's cast includes one Oscar winner: Angelina Jolie; and two Oscar nominees: Imelda Staunton and Lesley Manville. Pax Jolie-Pitt, Zahara Jolie-Pitt: Angelina Jolie's children appear briefly, cowering in fear of Maleficent during the christening scene. The name "Maleficent" is derived from Latin and literally means "evil doer". There is no reason given in the film for Maleficent, as a young, good fairy, to have such a name. When she does start to become destructive, the name matches.

text: 1 year old already! author: @GeirOlavDrablos
text: Are Disney in a woke-war against men? After this film i'm not longer in doubt. I just saw the sequel to "Maleficent" with Angelina Jolie. In fact, a Disney movie coined for children. No man has a role of significance in the film. The men who are there must find themselves playing supporting roles; weak, worthless or unconscious (literally, the king lies in a coma through most of the film). Women are the strongest forces, on both sides. The Queen, played by Michelle Pfeiffer, spins a plot so viciously that I think no man could make it up. But who executes her orders? Armies of men. I don't think we'll see an army of women led by a man. But the opposite is obviously not only accepted, but desirable. Also this message is clear; men get to find themselves in women at the top! It is also the men who have to pay the price when the queen (woman) loses. They're being slaughtered in droves. But who's fighting on the good side? Both men and women. It is suddenly okay to have a more balanced distribution between the sexes. The Queen herself? She is transformed into a goat towards the end of the film, but gets to keep her life. Had a man in the same villainous role gotten away with life? The answer we have already received, in the first film about Malificent. Back then, her nemesis was a man. He died at the end of the film, having fallen from a tall building.
